graphy: Fictional Representation of National Identity in Graham Swift, Peter Carey, and Mordecai Richler -- tSaleem Fathered by Oskar: Midnight's Children, Magic Realism, and The Tin Drum -- tMagical Archetypes: Midlife Miracles in The Satanic Verses -- tDerek Walcott and Alejo Carpentier: Nature, History, and the Caribbean Writer -- tIV. Community -- tMagic Realism as Postcolonial Discourse -- tMetoikoi and Magical Realism in the Maghrebian Narratives of Tahar ben Jelloun and Abdelkebir Khatibi -- tThe Magic of Identity: Magic Realism in Modern Japanese Fiction -- tRoads of "Exquisite Mysterious Muck": The Magical Journey through the City in William Kennedy's Ironweed, John Cheever's "The Enormous Radio," and Donald Barthelme's "City Life" -- tMagical Romance/Magical Realism: Ghosts in U.S. and Latin American Fiction -- tSelected Bibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMagical realism is often regarded as a regional trend, restricted to the Latin American writers who popularized it as a literary form. In this critical anthology, the first of its kind, editors Lois Parkinson Zamora and Wendy B. Faris show magical realism to be an international movement with a wide-ranging history and a significant influence among the literatures of the world. In essays on texts by writers as diverse as Toni Morrison, Günter Grass, Salman Rushdie, Derek Walcott, Abe Kobo, Gabriel García Márquez, and many others, magical realism is examined as a worldwide phenomenon.Presenting the first English translation of Franz Roh's 1925 essay in which the term magical realism was coined, as well as Alejo Carpentier's classic 1949 essay that introduced the concept of lo real maravilloso to the Americas, this anthology begins by tracing the foundations of magical realism from its origins in the art world to its current literary contexts. It offers a broad range of critical perspectives and theoretical approaches to this movement, as well as intensive analyses of various cultural traditions and individual texts from Eastern Europe, Asia, North America, Africa, the Caribbean, and Australia, in addition to those from Latin America. In situating magical realism within the expanse of literary and cultural history, this collection describes a mode of writing that has been a catalyst in the development of new regional literatures and a revitalizing force for more established narrative traditions-writing particularly alive in postcolonial contexts and a major component of postmodernist fiction.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aFictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aMagic realism (Literature). 0aSpanish American fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / Hispanic American.2bisacsh1 aCarpentier, Alejo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChanady, Amaryll, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlores, Angel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMikics, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFaris, Wendy B., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRoh, Franz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuenther, Irene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDelbaere-Garant, Jeanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoster Jr., John Burt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErickson, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThiem, Jon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZamora, Lois Parkinson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id